\begin_layout Standard
Conditional probability enables us to consider the outcome of an experiment
 with partial information.In the same way, a generic formula for P(E|F) that
 is valid for all events E and F is derived:If the event F happens, then
 for E to occur, the actual occurrence must be a point in both E and F;
 that is, it must be in EF.Now that we know F has occurred, F becomes our
 new and reduced sample space; hence, the likelihood that the event EF happens
 equals the probability of EF relative to the probability of F.That is, we
 have the definition below.
 If $$ (F) > 0 $$ then P(E If E and F are independent events, that is to
 say, if F occurs, then that gives us no information about occurance of
 E then $$ E The probability model is 
