\begin_layout Section
Local Causality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the previous section, some student wrote the definition of events in
 probability theory and in theory of relativity.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X,Y$
\end_inset

 random variables taking value 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ -1,1\right\} $
\end_inset

 and, let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 some settings, or degenerate rv.
 The probability spaces involved are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\left\{ -1,1\right\} ,\mathcal{F}\left(\left\{ -1,1\right\} \right),P_{X}\left(\cdot|A,B\right)\right)$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\left\{ -1,1\right\} ,\mathcal{F}\left(\left\{ -1,1\right\} \right),P_{Y}\left(\cdot|A,B\right)\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
,
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\left\{ -1,1\right\} ,\mathcal{F}\left(\left\{ -1,1\right\} \right),\delta_{A}\left(\cdot-\vartheta_{A}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\left\{ -1,1\right\} ,\mathcal{F}\left(\left\{ -1,1\right\} \right),\delta_{B}\left(\cdot-\vartheta_{B}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The setting can be modelized as a.
 By the multiplication formula (see slides) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P\left(X,Y|A,B\right)=P\left(X|Y,A,B\right)P\left(Y|A,B\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Suppose that the values of the random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X,Y$
\end_inset

 depends on the settings 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B$
\end_inset

.
 Now, consider the situation where the rv are spacelike separate such that
 the probability spaces are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\left\{ -1,1\right\} ,\mathcal{F}\left(\left\{ -1,1\right\} \right),P_{X}\left(\cdot|A\right)\right)$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\left\{ -1,1\right\} ,\mathcal{F}\left(\left\{ -1,1\right\} \right),P_{Y}\left(\cdot|B\right)\right)$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\left\{ -1,1\right\} ,\mathcal{F}\left(\left\{ -1,1\right\} \right),\delta_{A}\left(\cdot-\vartheta_{A}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\left\{ -1,1\right\} ,\mathcal{F}\left(\left\{ -1,1\right\} \right),\delta_{B}\left(\cdot-\vartheta_{B}\right)\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
then,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P\left(X,Y|A,B\right)=P\left(X|A\right)P\left(Y|B\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

However, if they show some correlations, we assume that there must be some
 local structure.
 Therefore we rewrite the probability spaces as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\left\{ -1,1\right\} ,\mathcal{F}\left(\left\{ -1,1\right\} \right),P_{X}\left(\cdot|A,\Lambda\right)\right)$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\left\{ -1,1\right\} ,\mathcal{F}\left(\left\{ -1,1\right\} \right),P_{Y}\left(\cdot|B,\Lambda\right)\right)$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\left\{ -1,1\right\} ,\mathcal{F}\left(\left\{ -1,1\right\} \right),\delta_{A}\left(\cdot-\vartheta_{A}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\left\{ -1,1\right\} ,\mathcal{F}\left(\left\{ -1,1\right\} \right),\delta_{B}\left(\cdot-\vartheta_{B}\right)\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
then,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P\left(X,Y|A,B,\Lambda\right)=P\left(X|A,\Lambda\right)P\left(Y|B,\Lambda\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This is call screening–off condition and can obtained equivalently with
 parameter independence and outcome independence (Jarrett 1984).
 Even more, the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 is motivated by the Reichenbach's common cause principle.
\end_layout

